"Don’t tell me!" that woman had commanded. "I’ll have it in a moment. Some profession. I can 
see you with a brief case." He had not intended to tell her. Some subjects were dinner conversation; 
some were not. But she had gone on.

They hurried on; he was not in the lobby. The Midway-Copton is not a large building, nor 
swank—else they could not have rented there. It has but two elevators. One was down and empty; 
the other, by the indicator, had just started up.

"He said—" Randall stopped, realizing that Potbury had not said anything specific against Hoag; 
it had been entirely what he did not say. "It wasn’t so much what he said; it was how he felt about 
you. He hates you, Hoag—and he is afraid of you."

Randall told him; Hoag nodded. "I see. Truthfully, I do not recall it, even today, although my full 
persona knows of it. Jonathan Hoag had a nervous habit of polishing things with his handkerchief;
erhaps he polished the arm of your chair."

"You have no idea. I don’t mean learning how to dress, or not walking into the wrong rest room; 
I learned those in the hospital. But how could I live? What job could I get? Hell, I couldn’t even 
drive a car. I didn’t know a trade; I couldn’t do manual labor—too much scar tissue, too tender.

They went back down a floor by stair and looked up room 2013. Pete tried the knob cautiously; 
the door was locked. He knocked on it—no answer. He pressed an ear to it and thought he could 
hear movement inside. He stepped back, frowning.

"Use your imagination, man. Consider the top of the first cube in relation to the top of the second; 
that’s cube number three. Then the two bottom squares, then the front faces of each cube, the back 
faces, the right hand, the left hand—eight cubes." He pointed them out.
